Regarding your question about generating a table of contents automatically in a LATEX document, here's an example of how you can do it:

First, you need to include the `tableofcontents` package in your LATEX document's preamble:
```
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tableofcontents}
```
Next, you can use the `toc` command to generate the table of contents. Here's an example:
```
\begin{document}
\tableofcontents
\section{Introduction}
\section{Section 1}
\section{Section 2}
\section{Section 3}
\end{document}
```
This will generate a table of contents with the section headings as the entries.

If you want to customize the appearance of the table of contents, you can use other commands provided by the `tableofcontents` package, such as `tocstyle` and `cftocstyle`. For example, to change the font size and color of the section headings in the table of contents, you can use the following commands:
```
\usepackage[tocstyle]{article}
\renewcommand\cfttocfont{\Large\bfseries}
\renewcommand\cfttocpagefont{\normalsize\color{gray}}
```
This will change the font size and color of the section headings in the table of contents.

