Certainly! To draw a chessboard using LATEX, we can use the `tikz` package to create the board and the `chess` package to add the chess pieces. Here's an example code that should produce a neat and professional-looking chessboard:

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usepackage{chess}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}
% Set the size of the board
\setchesboardsize{8cm}{8cm}

% Draw the board
\draw (0,0) grid (8,8);

% Add the chess pieces
\setchespiece{king}{white}{whiteKing}{blackKing}
\setchespiece{queen}{white}{whiteQueen}{blackQueen}
\setchespiece{rook}{white}{whiteRook}{blackRook}
\setchespiece{bishop}{white}{whiteBishop}{blackBishop}
\setchespiece{knight}{white}{whiteKnight}{blackKnight}
\setchespiece{pawn}{white}{whitePawn}{blackPawn}

% Add the labels
\node at (1.5,1.5) {a1};
\node at (1.5,6.5) {a8};
\node at (8.5,1.5) {h1};
\node at (8.5,6.5) {h8};

\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}

This code will produce a chessboard with the standard 8x8 grid, and will place the chess pieces in their starting positions. The `grid` command from the `tikz` package is used to draw the board, and the `setchespiece` commands from the `chess` package are used to place the chess pieces. The `node` commands are used to add the labels to the board.

Note that you will need to have the `tikz` and `chess` packages installed in your LaTeX distribution in order to use this code. You can install these packages using your package manager or by downloading them from the CTAN website.

